2) Structure Tensor S as a tensor object

Your original S=(E,Ro,I) becomes a bundle of tensors.

2.1 Entity–Role assignment as a tensor

Let entity-role assignment be a bilinear form:

A \in E \otimes R

Interpretation: A_{ir} = strength / certainty that entity e_i occupies role r.

If you want multi-role / multi-context:

A \in E \otimes R \otimes \Xi

where \Xi indexes contexts (scene, chapter, proof phase, decision mode).

2.2 Structural relations as a tensor

Relations between entities (graph/hypergraph):
	•	pairwise: B \in E \otimes E
	•	typed relations: B \in E \otimes E \otimes \Tau

This captures “who depends on whom”, “causal edges”, “proof dependency”, etc.

2.3 Invariants as constraint tensors

Represent invariants as a set of constraint functionals. The clean tensor way:

I := \{ \phi_k \}_{k=1}^m,\quad \phi_k \in K^\*, \quad K = \text{features}(A,B,\dots)

and a feature map:

\Psi: (A,B,\dots) \mapsto z \in K

Invariant satisfaction is:

\phi_k(\Psi(S)) \le 0 \quad \forall k

So Structure Tensor is:

S := (A,B,\Psi,\{\phi_k\})

This is now mathematically real: tensors + linear functionals (or convex constraints).

