3) Tension Tensor T as a tensor object

Your T=(Q,Co,G,U) becomes a direct-sum tensor living in a tension space:

\mathcal{T} := P \oplus C \oplus G \oplus U

and the tension tensor is:

T \in \mathcal{T}

If you want strict tensor product form (instead of direct sum), use a block tensor:

T \in (P \otimes \mathbf{e}_Q)\ \oplus\ (C \otimes \mathbf{e}_{Co})\ \oplus\ (G \otimes \mathbf{e}_G)\ \oplus\ (U \otimes \mathbf{e}_U)

Tension magnitude

Define a norm (domain-chosen):

|T| := \|T\|_{\mathcal{T}}

Common choices:
	•	weighted ℓ₂: \|T\|^2 = w_Q\|Q\|^2+w_C\|Co\|^2+w_G\|G\|^2+w_U\|U\|^2
	•	ℓ₁ for “count-like” tension.

