4) Beats as operators (Beat Algebra becomes operator algebra)

A beat is an admissible state transformation:

4.1 State space

Let the full NTE state be:

Y := \mathcal{S} \times \mathcal{T}

where \mathcal{S} is the space of valid structure representations (A,B,\dots).

4.2 Beat as an operator

A beat is a map:

b: Y \to Y

To make “tensor algebra” explicit, define a beat as a pair of operators:

b \equiv (b_S, b_T)
b_S:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{S},\quad b_T:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}

If you want linearity:

b_S(S,T)=M_S S + N_S T,\quad b_T(S,T)=M_T T + N_T S

with M_S, M_T linear maps induced by tensors in \mathcal{L}(\cdot).
If you want realism (most narratives), allow controlled nonlinearity but keep constraints convex.

4.3 Beat composition = operator composition

Define:

b_2 \circ b_1

Associative, generally non-commutative. Identity beat is identity operator on Y.

So your “beat algebra” becomes a monoid (or category) of admissible operators:

\mathcal{B} \subseteq \text{End}(Y)

