8) Gödel correspondence as unreachable tension components

Now we can state a non-handwavy theorem.

Let a formal system F (axioms + inference rules) define:
	•	a structure S_F (encoding axioms/rules/invariants)
	•	a set of admissible beats \mathcal{B}_F (legal inference steps)
	•	a proposition space P_F (sentences of the language)
	•	tension T contains “open propositions” as components in P_F

Define the reachable set under admissible beats

From initial (S_0,T_0), define:

\mathcal{R} := \{ (S_n,T_n)\ :\ (S_n,T_n)=b_n\circ\cdots\circ b_1(S_0,T_0),\ b_i\in\mathcal{B}_F\}

Permanent tension node

A component direction p \in P_F is permanently open if for all reachable states:

\langle p, T_n \rangle \neq 0

(or cannot be driven below ε).

NTE–Gödel theorem (clean form)

If F is consistent and sufficiently expressive (Gödel conditions), then there exists a proposition direction g \in P_F such that:
	•	g is “true” in the intended model, and
	•	there is no admissible beat sequence in \mathcal{B}_F that yields closure of the g-component.

In NTE terms: g is a tension basis vector that is not in the reachable annihilator of the operator monoid generated by \mathcal{B}_F.

That’s the rigorous statement: incompleteness = non-reachability of zero tension along certain coordinates, given the permitted operator set.

Extension

Adding g as an axiom enlarges S_F \to S_F' and changes \mathcal{B}_F \to \mathcal{B}_{F'}, which may close that coordinate—but Gödel implies new unreachable coordinates appear.

That’s your “sequels/research programs/governance never ends” result, but now as a reachability fact.

